Securely Store and Manage Passwords in Ubuntu
Step 1: Install KeePassXC
1.1 Update Your System
Open your terminal and run:

 
 
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y
1.2 Install KeePassXC
 
 
sudo apt install keepassxc -y
Step 2: Create a New Database
2.1 Launch KeePassXC
Open KeePassXC from your applications menu or run:

 
 
keepassxc &
2.2 Create a New Database
Open KeePassXC.
Click on "Create New Database".
Follow the prompts to set up your new database. Enter a strong master password and click "Next".
Save your database file with a .kdbx extension to a secure location.
Step 3: Add Entries
3.1 Add a New Entry
In KeePassXC, click on the "Add New Entry" button (a green plus icon).
Fill in the title, username, and password fields.
Click on the "Generate" button next to the password field to create a strong password.
3.2 Save the Entry
Click "OK" to save the entry.
Step 4: Organize Your Entries
4.1 Create Groups
Right-click on the database tree and select "Add Group".
Name the group (e.g., "Work", "Personal", etc.).
4.2 Move Entries to Groups
Drag and drop entries into the appropriate groups.
Step 5: Backup Your Database
5.1 Manual Backup
 
 
cp /path/to/your/database.kdbx /path/to/backup/location/
5.2 Automatic Backup (using cron job)
Open the crontab file:
 
 
crontab -e
Add the following line to schedule a daily backup at 2 AM:
 
 
0 2 * * * cp /path/to/your/database.kdbx /path/to/backup/location/
Step 6: Enable Two-Factor Authentication (Optional)
6.1 Set Up a YubiKey
Plug in your YubiKey.
In KeePassXC, go to "Database" > "Database Settings".
Under "Two-Channel Auto-Type Obfuscation", click "Set Up" and follow the prompts.
Step 7: Secure Your System
7.1 Lock KeePassXC When Not in Use
In KeePassXC, go to "Tools" > "Settings" > "Security".
Set the auto-lock timeout (e.g., 5 minutes).
7.2 Use a Strong Master Password
Ensure your master password is long, complex, and unique.
Step 8: Use the Browser Extension (Optional)
8.1 Install the Browser Extension
Go to your browser's extension store and search for "KeePassXC-Browser".
Install the extension.
8.2 Enable Browser Integration
In KeePassXC, go to "Tools" > "Settings" > "Browser Integration".
Enable the browsers you want to integrate with and follow the setup instructions.
Step 9: Regular Maintenance
9.1 Update Entries
Regularly update your passwords and entries in KeePassXC.
9.2 Review Security Settings
Periodically review and update the security settings in KeePassXC.
By following these steps and commands, you can securely store and manage your passwords on Ubuntu using KeePassXC.
